<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911017-0118</DOCNO><DOCID>911017-0118.</DOCID><HL>   Marketing andamp; Media:   MGM-Pathe Appoints   Gradinger President   Of a Television Unit</HL><DATE>10/17/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8</SO><CO>   PCC WNEWS</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>ENTERTAINMENT AND LEISURE (ENT)MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY (REC)</IN><NS>PERSONNEL ANNOUNCEMENTS, PROMOTIONS, APPOINTMENTS (PER)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   CULVER CITY, Calif. -- MGM-Pathe Communications Co.'sMGM/UA Television Production Group unit named Ed Gradingerpresident, succeeding Lynn Loring, who resigned in July.   Mr. Gradinger, 51 years old, will report to David Gerber,chairman and chief executive officer of MGM WorldwideTelevision Group. The appointment reunites the twoexecutives, who worked together at Columbia PicturesTelevision in the late 1970s.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Gradinger said he was president and chief executive ofNew World Entertainment Ltd. until the end of 1989. Sixmonths before his departure, the movie and television concernwas acquired by Ron Perelman's Andrews Group Inc.   Mr. Gradinger also was previously senior executive vicepresident and chief operating officer of Twentieth CenturyFox Television, where he was involved with such programs as&quot;L.A. Law&quot; and &quot;The Fall Guy.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>